 \n\nThe food itself was very good, I've had many a fish dish and everyone pretty much liked their food. However, as we have been there, we've noticed that they never have enough staff around and sometimes there are long waits. We have a large group and we also have a few small kids with us which makes the experience that much more stressful, but once you get there and seated, things get much easier. As a matter of fact, we had to walk a step further out from the payphone booth to get attention because there was no host up front. \n\nTo add to the stressful aspect, there are a lot of large trees, such as the Evergreen, that do not allow children to go over them. They have some signs posted, but I wish they would take some responsibility for the trees, or else they will lose a lot of customers. They really need to spend staff training on basic forest etiquette so they will be much better at having kids stay with the trees. Even with that, we did manage to get some large fir trees and a Douglas fir tree that actually looks like it is dying, but I'm not sure what happened there. \n\nAll in all, I'm certainly surprised that there is a restaurant that is successful in the metro. I am also happy that there are folks who are willing to take the initiative to take care of a park, and it makes me very proud to have the opportunity to show them that they are indeed succeeding. We will be back, perhaps not just for the food, but for being a true leader in their community.<|endoftext|>
